      Credit Suisse
   =20
 =20

Here is the basic situation at Credit Suisse Group AG. It had a lot of liab=
ilities (bank deposits, derivatives, etc.). It had a lot of assets (bonds, =
loans, derivatives, etc.). If you valued those assets and liabilities using=
 US generally accepted accounting principles
  [1]
=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0the rules that Credit Suisse uses to  publish its fina=
ncial statements=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0then the assets were worth quite a lot=
 more than the liabilities, and Credit Suisse was solvent and doing great, =
last month and also today. If you valued those assets and liabilities using=
 Swiss regulatory capital accounting rules =E2=80=94=C2=A0the slightly diff=
erent set of rules that Swiss regulators use to decide if Credit Suisse is =
well capitalized =E2=80=94=C2=A0then, again, the assets were worth quite a =
lot more than the liabilities, and Credit Suisse was solvent and well capit=
alized and doing great, last month and also today. Under the somewhat styli=
zed accounting conventions that govern Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s life, Credit=
 Suisse was just fine. It had assets, it had liabilities, the liabilities w=
ere worth more than the assets, it was all very normal.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CCredi=
t Suisse meets the higher capital and liquidity requirements applicable to =
systemically important banks,=E2=80=9D Swiss regulators announced=C2=A0on M=
arch 15.
Then there was a banking crisis and a run on Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s deposi=
ts. And in the=C2=A0crisis it turned out that the accounting conventions di=
d not quite reflect economic reality. In particular:
=09If Credit Suisse had to=C2=A0sell all of its assets at once, it would no=
t be able to sell them for the value reflected on its books.=09If someone h=
ad to=C2=A0assume all of Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s liabilities at once, they =
might worry about liabilities =E2=80=94=C2=A0lawsuits, investigations, etc.=
 =E2=80=94 that were not reflected on its books.

And the run on deposits created a situation in which someone=C2=A0did=C2=A0=
need to buy all of Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s assets and assume all of its lia=
bilities all at once: Credit Suisse couldn=E2=80=99t continue operating on =
its own if all the deposits fled and it had to sell all its assets to pay t=
hem. And so over the weekend of March 18 and 19, UBS Group AG bought Credit=
 Suisse. And the price it paid reflected the fact that,=C2=A0that weekend,=
=C2=A0Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s assets were worth=C2=A0much less than its lia=
bilities, to UBS. Specifically:
=09For accounting purposes, Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s assets were worth rough=
ly 43 billion Swiss francs more than its liabilities.
  [2]
=C2=A0(The assets were worth on the order of CHF 500 billion or so; the lia=
bilities were CHF 43 billion less than that.)=09UBS paid about CHF 3 billio=
n (in stock) for Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s equity, but was able to cancel abo=
ut CHF 16 billion of its liabilities =E2=80=94=C2=A0its additional tier 1 c=
apital securities, which got written down to zero due to the deal =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and so paid a net price of negative CHF 13 billion.=09CHF 43 billion =
minus negative CHF 13 billion is negative CHF 56 billion.

UBS got all of Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s assets at a discount of CHF 56 billi=
on: The liabilities it assumed, plus the stock that it paid, totaled CHF 56=
 billion less than the value of the=C2=A0assets that it got.
What does this mean? There are about three possible answers:
=09UBS got an incredible deal; it got CHF 500 billion of financial assets a=
t a 10% discount for being in the right place at the right time.=09The asse=
ts were not really worth what Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s financial statements =
said they were worth.=09There are hidden liabilities that are not reflected=
 on the financial statements and that UBS will ultimately have to pay for.

The correct answer is surely some combination of all three. UBS got Credit =
Suisse at a CHF 56 billion discount; this discount is, in accounting, refer=
red to as =E2=80=9Cbadwill.=E2=80=9D Some of that badwill will end up going=
 to pay for losses on the assets: If there=E2=80=99s some bond that was on =
the balance sheet at CHF 1,000, and UBS ends up selling it at CHF 980, then=
 it will have a CHF 20 loss that will effectively reduce the badwill. Some =
of the badwill will end up going to pay for additional liabilities: If some=
one sues Credit Suisse for CHF 1 million and wins, UBS will pay the CHF 1 m=
illion and that will reduce the badwill. But some of it will probably be le=
ft over: If UBS ends up losing CHF 30 billion on Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s as=
sets and paying an extra CHF 10 billion of liabilities, it will have 16 bil=
lion of badwill left, and that will be its =E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D discount =
for buying Credit Suisse, its economic profit from doing the deal.
All of this is just about how accounting does not match=C2=A0perfectly with=
 reality. From a financial or regulatory accounting perspective, Credit Sui=
sse was doing great, and still is. From an economic perspective, not. From =
an accounting perspective, UBS got a CHF 56 billion discount when it bought=
 Credit Suisse. From an economic perspective, UBS paid about=C2=A0as much a=
s it was willing to pay for Credit Suisse. That CHF 56 billion is, roughly,=
 the gap between accounting and reality.
Anyway Credit Suisse is still technically independent =E2=80=94=C2=A0the de=
al is supposed to close in May =E2=80=94=C2=A0and both  Credit Suisse and  =
UBS reported earnings this week. When you report earnings, you use accounti=
ng. When accounting does not match reality, the earnings are weird. Credit =
Suisse, which in reality=C2=A0went bust last quarter, in accounting terms  =
had its best quarter ever:

The Swiss bank lost more than $2 billion from its businesses in the first q=
uarter, but posted a prodigious net profit because of the paper gains reali=
zed from writing off $17 billion in bonds. =E2=80=A6
Credit Suisse posted a 12.43 billion Swiss franc net profit, equivalent to =
$13.9 billion, for the first three months of the year because of the value =
of the written-off bonds. The bank lurched through financial losses and sca=
ndals in the past several years, and failed in a last attempt to restructur=
e and regain trust after bank customers started pulling their deposits and =
investments last fall.
The massive quarterly profit, the largest in the bank=E2=80=99s history and=
 among the largest ever for a bank, is an unusual coda given the bank=E2=80=
=99s unraveling.
It was possible because the write-down of the bonds feeds through as a reve=
nue gain, which leads to a swelling of paper profits. But it isn=E2=80=99t =
money that Credit Suisse shareholders will immediately realize. UBS benefit=
s, however, since it inherits Credit Suisse without having to repay those b=
onds. Credit Suisse shareholders will receive UBS stock once the deal compl=
etes.

Credit Suisse is still an independent bank, and as a technical accounting m=
atter if it   wrote down $17 billion of additional tier 1 capital securitie=
s to zero, that=E2=80=99s $17 billion of profit. Those are the rules. The f=
act that it wrote down those securities=C2=A0because it collapsed is of eco=
nomic interest, but not relevant to the accounting.
Also, because Credit Suisse was, as an accounting matter, well capitalized =
before, during and after its collapse, it is now=C2=A0extremely=C2=A0well c=
apitalized, because all of those liabilities went to zero. It reported a co=
mmon equity tier 1 capital ratio of 14.1% at the end of 2022, well above re=
