Let=E2=80=99s say there=E2=80=99s a smallish public company that you like. =
To make things more concrete, say it=E2=80=99s Getty Images Holdings Inc., =
which went public last year by merging with a special purpose acquisition c=
ompany; last Friday its stock closed at $5.06 per share, for an equity mark=
et capitalization of $2 billion. You buy some stock, expecting it to go up.=
 It does not go up. You think the company could do a better job =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0you think it has a valuable business but management is not maximizing=
 its potential =E2=80=94=C2=A0so you send some letters to the executives an=
d board of directors with your ideas for improvements. You get no answer, a=
nd things do not improve.
You decide that these people don=E2=80=99t know what they=E2=80=99re doing =
and that the only way to maximize the company=E2=80=99s potential is if som=
eone buys the company, fires management, and runs it in the way that you th=
ink is better. And you think that someone=C2=A0would=C2=A0do that: The comp=
any is valuable but mismanaged, and a smart buyer could pay a premium for i=
t and still make a lot of money by running it right.
So you send some more letters to the board saying =E2=80=9Chey you should h=
ire bankers to run an auction and find someone to buy the company.=E2=80=9D=
 Still no response.
Now what do you do? Well:
=09Send more letters? That=E2=80=99s not going very well.=09
You=C2=A0could go out and find someone to buy the company. Call up potentia=
l buyers, explain the value proposition, and get one of them to pay, say, $=
4 billion to buy the whole company at a premium. This is hard, though, beca=
use you don=E2=80=99t work there and can=E2=80=99t really commit to anythin=
g on behalf of the company. You could call up a big private equity firm and=
 say =E2=80=9Chey you should buy Getty Images,=E2=80=9D and they will say =
=E2=80=9Chmm maybe, when can we start due diligence,=E2=80=9D and you will =
say =E2=80=9Coh I don=E2=80=99t know I don=E2=80=99t work there, why don=E2=
=80=99t you call them?=E2=80=9D Not that helpful. (In the specific case of =
Getty, it=E2=80=99s even harder, because three big shareholders =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0the Getty family, Koch Industries Inc. and Neuberger Berman Group LLC=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0combine to own about 85% of the company and control the boa=
rd, so it=E2=80=99s not like a hostile deal is possible: Any potential buye=
r would have to work with the board.)=09
You=C2=A0could buy the whole company yourself. But it=E2=80=99s not like yo=
u have $4 billion lying around.

There is =E2=80=94=C2=A0and this is not legal or investing or M&A or any ot=
her sort of advice =E2=80=94=C2=A0another option, sort of a combination of =
Options 2 and 3. It goes like this. You=C2=A0put out a press release offeri=
ng to buy the company yourself. =E2=80=9CI will buy this company at $10 per=
 share, or $4 billion total,=E2=80=9D you say. Because you do not have $4 b=
illion, you make it clear in the press release that your offer is contingen=
t on financing, and on the board engaging with you.
What will happen? Well, maybe the board will call you up and say =E2=80=9Ch=
ey, you=E2=80=99re right, we=E2=80=99d love to sell for $4 billion.=E2=80=
=9D Then you start due diligence, you learn about the company, you negotiat=
e a deal, and you figure out if it=E2=80=99s really worth $4 billion. If it=
 is, you call up some private equity firms and say =E2=80=9Chey, I=E2=80=99=
ve got this great deal to buy Getty Images, all I need is $4 billion, are y=
ou in?=E2=80=9D And you bring them in and they do due diligence and maybe t=
hey agree to put up the $4 billion to finance your deal.
Or maybe all of the private equity firms pass, and then you go back to the =
board and say =E2=80=9Chey thanks it=E2=80=99s been great dealing with you =
but my financing fell through, and the deal was contingent on financing, so=
 there=E2=80=99s no deal.=E2=80=9D And then you shake hands and walk away f=
riends, and maybe the board is inspired by your efforts and=C2=A0they=C2=A0=
will go find a buyer.
Or maybe the board continues to ignore you, you can=E2=80=99t do due dilige=
nce, so you can=E2=80=99t get anyone else interested, so you can=E2=80=99t =
raise any financing. Then you=E2=80=99re not any=C2=A0worse=C2=A0off than y=
ou were before. You were on the outside, asking the board to sell the compa=
ny, and now you=E2=80=99re still on the outside, asking the board to sell t=
he company. But you=E2=80=99re a little better off, because you are asking =
the board to sell the company in a higher-profile, higher-pressure way. =E2=
=80=9CI am offering to buy the company for $4 billion=E2=80=9D creates a li=
ttle more pressure on the board to respond than =E2=80=9CI would like you t=
o sell the company to someone else for $4 billion.=E2=80=9D The board has s=
ome sort of fiduciary obligation to consider any real takeover offer. Is th=
is a real takeover offer? Well! Well.
Also let=E2=80=99s be clear here, you are better off in another way, which =
is that when you put out a press release offering to buy the company at a h=
uge premium, the stock will go up. And you own some stock. Something to thi=
nk about!
Is this =E2=80=A6=C2=A0is this what you would call a=C2=A0fake=C2=A0takeove=
r offer? I don=E2=80=99t know! On the one hand, you are offering to buy the=
 company for $4 billion, and you don=E2=80=99t have $4 billion, so there is=
 something a bit off about that. On the other hand, you did=C2=A0say=C2=A0t=
hat your offer was contingent on financing and due diligence. =E2=80=9CI wi=
ll buy this company for $4 billion if someone will give me $4 billion,=E2=
=80=9D is the essential content of your announcement. Could be true! Anyone=
 could buy a company for $4 billion, if someone gave them $4 billion, and i=
f the company agreed to sell. Those are big ifs, but they are right in the =
announcement.
Anyway here is an extremely fun press release that=C2=A0Trillium Capital LL=
C put out yesterday titled =E2=80=9CTrillium Capital Isssues Proposal to Ac=
quire Getty Images for $10 Per Share,=E2=80=9D yes with four s=E2=80=99s in=
