A schematic picture of US regional banks goes something like this. In 2021,=
 banks were borrowing at 0% by taking deposits from customers in accounts t=
hat paid no interest, and they were lending at 3% by making mortgage loans =
or buying Treasury bonds. In 2023, depositors are less interested in deposi=
t accounts that pay no interest, since they can get 5% interest on safe sho=
rt-term investments like  Treasury bills or money market funds. Meanwhile t=
he market interest rates on mortgages and Treasury bonds have also gone up;=
 the 10-year Treasury yields about 3.4% and   mortgage rates are at like 6.=
4%.
That is potentially bad news for banks. There are two ways for that to go. =
It can be=C2=A0acutely=C2=A0bad news. Acute bad news looks like this:
=09A bank=E2=80=99s=C2=A0assets =E2=80=94=C2=A0its bonds and loans =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0have=C2=A0lost value:=C2=A0If you have $100 million=C2=A0of 3% mor=
tgages, and mortgage rates are now 6%, your old 3% mortgages might be worth=
 $85 million.
  [4]
=C2=A0You have a large mark-to-market loss on your assets because interest =
rates have moved against you.=09Meanwhile the bank=E2=80=99s depositors wil=
l=C2=A0take their money out, because (1) they can get more interest elsewhe=
re and/or (2) they are worried about the bank=E2=80=99s=C2=A0solvency becau=
se of all the mark-to-market losses on its assets.=09The bank needs to get =
cash to pay those depositors, which it does by selling bonds and loans, but=
 since those are less valuable than they used to be it can=E2=80=99t raise =
enough money.=09The bank goes bust, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. sei=
zes it, it pays out depositors and it auctions off the assets at a loss.

This acute bad news is more or less what happened to Silicon Valley Bank la=
st month. Standard bank-run stuff.
But it could also be=C2=A0chronically=C2=A0bad news, which is probably less=
 bad. Chronic bad news looks like this:
=09Never mind the stuff about the assets losing value. That is a matter of =
accounting, and you can ignore it. If you have $100 million of 3% mortgages=
, and mortgage rates are now 6%, you still have $100 million of 3% mortgage=
s. They will still pay you back $100 million=C2=A0plus interest. It=E2=80=
=99s just that the interest is less than you=E2=80=99d like, less than the =
current market rate. You still have the same assets, but they pay you 3%;=
=C2=A0new=C2=A0assets would pay 6%.=09Meanwhile the bank=E2=80=99s deposito=
rs don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0take their money out:=C2=A0They just=C2=A0charge=C2=
=A0more. The bank keeps its deposits by=C2=A0paying interest=C2=A0to compet=
e with Treasury bills and money market funds.=C2=A0It doesn=E2=80=99t have =
any more depositors in zero-interest checking accounts, but it has deposito=
rs who get 5% on their savings accounts.=09The bank doesn=E2=80=99t need to=
 raise cash, it doesn=E2=80=99t sell assets, it doesn=E2=80=99t go bust, th=
e FDIC doesn=E2=80=99t seize it, everything is fine.=09It=E2=80=99s just th=
at, you know, it is earning 3% on its money and paying 5%, so it=E2=80=99s =
losing 2% each year. It is not=C2=A0profitable.=C2=A0Eventually=C2=A0it wil=
l run out of money.=09Meh! That can change. For one thing, those 3% mortgag=
es will mature, and the bank will make more mortgages at 6%; eventually its=
 assets will turn over and it will earn market interest rates on them. And =
as things stabilize a bit, it will probably get back more of its zero-inter=
est deposit accounts and pay a bit less for its money. Eventually things wi=
ll get back to normal and the bank will be paying 3% on deposits, earning 6=
% on loans, and making the same spread as it was before.
  [5]
=C2=A0It just has to weather some unpleasantness to get there.

This chronic bad news is more or less what is happening to First Republic B=
ank. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s   Jennifer Surane and Max Reyes report:

First Republic Bank=E2=80=99s quarterly results =E2=80=94 including a worse=
-than-expected drop in deposits =E2=80=94 reignited investor concerns about=
 prospects for its business, breaking with more than a week of industry ear=
nings reports that had broadly reassured the market.
The company=E2=80=99s shares fell 29% to $11.37, an all-time low in intrada=
y trading, at 9:38 a.m. in New York. The stock is down more than 90% this y=
ear.
Executives at the San Francisco-based lender laid out plans Monday for shor=
ing up the firm after its first-quarter results showed customer deposits pl=
unged 41% to $104.5 billion in the period. That missed the $137 billion ave=
rage of analyst estimates compiled by Bloomberg and came even after the cou=
ntry=E2=80=99s largest lenders parked $30 billion of their own cash there. =
=E2=80=A6
Analysts expressed concern that deposit flight has left the firm worse off =
than rivals, with higher funding costs squeezing its ability to generate pr=
ofits on loans.
=E2=80=9CFirst Republic is an idiosyncratic situation in terms of the magni=
tude of the stress that it=E2=80=99s under,=E2=80=9D said David Chiaverini,=
 an analyst with Wedbush Securities Inc. He predicts the firm will face ope=
rating losses over the next couple of years.

And  the Wall Street Journal notes:

The bank said it=C2=A0paid between 3% and 4.9% on loans=C2=A0from the Fed a=
nd FHLB in the quarter, on average.
This means First Republic is facing a grim and unusual situation where it m=
ay have to pay more on its liabilities than it is earning on its loans, ana=
lysts have said. In the first quarter, the bank=E2=80=99s loan book yielded=
 3.73%.=C2=A0
Rising rates have battered the value of First Republic=E2=80=99s mortgages =
and other loans. The bank=E2=80=99s balance sheet showed $166.1 billion of =
loans as of Dec. 31, at amortized cost. A footnote said their fair-market v=
alue was $143.9 billion. The $22.2 billion difference was greater than Firs=
t Republic=E2=80=99s $17.4 billion of total equity, or assets minus liabili=
ties.=C2=A0

Here is  the earnings release. First Republic had positive net income, and =
positive net interest income, for the first quarter. Its interest income on=
 loans was up year-over-year, presumably because some of its loans have flo=
ating interest rates and so pay more as interest rates go up. But its inter=
est expense was up about 2,100% year-over-year: It was paying $44 million o=
f interest in the first quarter of 2022, when deposits were basically free,=
 and $974 million in the first quarter of 2023, when they were not.=C2=A0
Also First Republic is not paying all that interest on=C2=A0deposits:=C2=A0=
Its deposits fell from $176 billion at the end of 2022 to $104 billion at t=
he end of March; the deposits were largely replaced by other borrowings=C2=
=A0from the Federal Reserve and the Federal Home Loan Banks, which tend to =
charge more-or-less market rates of interest instead of the 0% interest tha=
t it can still pay on some of its checking accounts. Also of those $104 bil=
lion of deposits, $30 billion was   deposited by a consortium of big banks =
trying to prop up First Republic, and presumably they=E2=80=99re getting in=
terest too.
One point here is that the difference between the acute and chronic bad new=
s is pretty much whether regulators (and Jamie Dimon) decide to rescue a ba=
nk or not. Silicon Valley Bank had huge deposit outflows, so it   ran out o=
f money, so it was closed. First Republic Bank had huge deposit outflows, b=
ut by that point the Federal Reserve had   created a new program to lend mo=
ney to banks against bonds that had lost value, and the big banks came toge=
ther to replace some of those deposits. The acute bad news is very easy to =
fix! (I mean, to turn into chronic bad news.)=C2=A0It just requires someone=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0the Fed, other big banks =E2=80=94=C2=A0to take the risk of=
 lending tens of billions of dollars to a bank that is losing money. If som=
eone will do that, then the bank can just sort of hang around losing money =
forever.
Another point here is that the chronic bad news makes it hard to find a per=
manent solution. The basic state of First Republic is that its assets are w=
orth less than its liabilities,=C2=A0as an economic matter, but it is well =
capitalized=C2=A0as a regulatory capital matter. This means that it can lim=
p along indefinitely, but nobody wants to buy it because the correct price =
for it is negative.
  [6]
=C2=A0Surane and Reyes:

First Republic ended last year with almost $27 billion in markdowns on loan=
s and a bevy of unrealized losses on Treasuries and other long-dated bonds =
on the company=E2=80=99s balance sheet. That was far greater than the rough=
ly $13 billion in tangible common equity it had at the time.
Executives confirmed on Monday that the firm is seeking strategic options. =
Bloomberg News previously reported that they have considered a sale of the =
entire bank. But its sizable unrealized losses =E2=80=94 which would have t=
o be crystallized in most deals =E2=80=94 have caused some buyers to balk a=
t the prospect, people with knowledge of the matter have said.

It=E2=80=99s pretty easy to lend to a zombie bank, but harder to buy one.

