<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Credit Suisse</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is the basic situation at Credit Suisse G=
roup AG. It had a lot of liabilities (bank deposits, derivatives, etc.). It=
 had a lot of assets (bonds, loans, derivatives, etc.). If you valued those=
 assets and liabilities using US generally accepted accounting principles<a=
 class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpa=
rent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0the rules that Credit Suisse uses to <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31280636.259437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uY3JlZGl0LXN1aXNzZS5jb20vbWVkaWEvYXNzZXRzL2NvcnBvcmF0ZS9kb2NzL2Fib3V0LXVzL2=
ludmVzdG9yLXJlbGF0aW9ucy9maW5hbmNpYWwtZGlzY2xvc3VyZXMvZmluYW5jaWFsLXJlcG9yd=
HMvY3NnLWFyLTIwMjItZW4ucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3922c6c9" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> pub=
lish its financial statements</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0then the assets were =
worth quite a lot more than the liabilities, and Credit Suisse was solvent =
and doing great, last month and also today. If you valued those assets and =
liabilities using Swiss regulatory capital accounting rules =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
the slightly different set of rules that Swiss regulators use to decide if =
Credit Suisse is well capitalized =E2=80=94=C2=A0then, again, the assets we=
re worth quite a lot more than the liabilities, and Credit Suisse was solve=
nt and well capitalized and doing great, last month and also today. Under t=
he somewhat stylized accounting conventions that govern Credit Suisse=E2=80=
=99s life, Credit Suisse was just fine. It had assets, it had liabilities, =
the liabilities were worth more than the assets, it was all very normal.=C2=
=A0=E2=80=9CCredit Suisse meets the higher capital and liquidity requiremen=
ts applicable to systemically important banks,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31280636.259437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmlub=
WEuY2gvZW4vbmV3cy8yMDIzLzAzLzIwMjMwMzE1LW1tLXN0YXRlbWVudC8/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB917fc3aa" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">Swiss regulators announced</a>=C2=A0on March 15.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Then there was a banking crisis and a run on C=
redit Suisse=E2=80=99s deposits. And in the=C2=A0crisis it turned out that =
the accounting conventions did not quite reflect economic reality. In parti=
cular:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If Credit Suisse had to=C2=A0<em>sell =
all of its assets at once</em>, it would not be able to sell them for the v=
alue reflected on its books.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If so=
meone had to=C2=A0<em>assume all of Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s liabilities at =
once</em>, they might worry about liabilities =E2=80=94=C2=A0lawsuits, inve=
stigations, etc. =E2=80=94 that were not reflected on its books.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And the run on deposits created a situation in=
 which someone=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0</em>need to buy all of Credit Suisse=E2=
=80=99s assets and assume all of its liabilities all at once: Credit Suisse=
 couldn=E2=80=99t continue operating on its own if all the deposits fled an=
d it had to sell all its assets to pay them. And so over the weekend of Mar=
ch 18 and 19, UBS Group AG bought Credit Suisse. And the price it paid refl=
ected the fact that,=C2=A0<em>that weekend,=C2=A0</em>Credit Suisse=E2=80=
=99s assets were worth=C2=A0much less than its liabilities, <em>to UBS</em>=
. Specifically:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">For accounting purposes, Credit Suisse=
=E2=80=99s assets were worth roughly 43 billion Swiss francs more than its =
liabilities.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-=
color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0(The assets were worth on the order of CHF 500 billion or so; the=
 liabilities were CHF 43 billion less than that.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">UBS paid about CHF 3 billion (in stock) for Credit Suisse=
=E2=80=99s equity, but was able to cancel about CHF 16 billion of its liabi=
lities =E2=80=94=C2=A0its additional tier 1 capital securities, which got w=
ritten down to zero due to the deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0and so paid a net price =
of negative CHF 13 billion.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">CHF 43=
 billion minus negative CHF 13 billion is negative CHF 56 billion.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">UBS got all of Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s assets =
at a discount of CHF 56 billion: The liabilities it assumed, plus the stock=
 that it paid, totaled CHF 56 billion less than the value of the=C2=A0asset=
s that it got.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What does this mean? There are about three pos=
sible answers:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">UBS got an incredible deal; it got CH=
F 500 billion of financial assets at a 10% discount for being in the right =
place at the right time.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The asset=
s were not really worth what Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s financial statements s=
aid they were worth.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There are hid=
den liabilities that are not reflected on the financial statements and that=
 UBS will ultimately have to pay for.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The correct answer is surely some combination =
of all three. UBS got Credit Suisse at a CHF 56 billion discount; this disc=
ount is, in accounting, referred to as =E2=80=9Cbadwill.=E2=80=9D Some of t=
hat badwill will end up going to pay for losses on the assets: If there=E2=
=80=99s some bond that was on the balance sheet at CHF 1,000, and UBS ends =
up selling it at CHF 980, then it will have a CHF 20 loss that will effecti=
vely reduce the badwill. Some of the badwill will end up going to pay for a=
dditional liabilities: If someone sues Credit Suisse for CHF 1 million and =
wins, UBS will pay the CHF 1 million and that will reduce the badwill. But =
some of it will probably be left over: If UBS ends up losing CHF 30 billion=
 on Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s assets and paying an extra CHF 10 billion of li=
abilities, it will have 16 billion of badwill left, and that will be its =
=E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D discount for buying Credit Suisse, its economic prof=
it from doing the deal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All of this is just about how accounting does =
not match=C2=A0perfectly with reality. From a financial or regulatory accou=
nting perspective, Credit Suisse was doing great, and still is. From an eco=
nomic perspective, not. From an accounting perspective, UBS got a CHF 56 bi=
llion discount when it bought Credit Suisse. From an economic perspective, =
UBS paid about=C2=A0as much as it was willing to pay for Credit Suisse. Tha=
t CHF 56 billion is, roughly, the gap between accounting and reality.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway Credit Suisse is still technically inde=
pendent =E2=80=94=C2=A0the deal is supposed to close in May =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
and both <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31280636.=
259437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY3JlZGl0LXN1aXNzZS5jb20vbWVkaWEvYXNzZXRzL2NvcnBvcmF0=
ZS9kb2NzL2Fib3V0LXVzL2ludmVzdG9yLXJlbGF0aW9ucy9maW5hbmNpYWwtZGlzY2xvc3VyZXM=
vcmVzdWx0cy9jc2ctZWFybmluZ3NyZWxlYXNlLTFxMjMucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
2d374300" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;"> Credit Suisse</a> and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/31280636.259437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudWJzLmNvbS9nbG9iYWwv=
ZW4vbWVkaWEvZGlzcGxheS1wYWdlLW5kcC9lbi0yMDIzMDQyNS0xcTIzLXF1YXJ0ZXJseS1yZXN=
1bHQuaHRtbD9jYWFzSUQ9Q0FBUy1BY3Rpdml0eVN0cmVhbQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdb=
13525b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;"> UBS</a> reported earnings this week. When you report earni=
ngs, you use accounting. When accounting does not match reality, the earnin=
gs are weird. Credit Suisse, which in reality=C2=A0<em>went bust last quart=
er</em>, in accounting terms <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/31280636.259437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9jcmVkaXQt=
c3Vpc3NlLWRldGFpbHMtcGFpbmZ1bC1maW5hbC1kYXlzLWJlZm9yZS1yZXNjdWUtZjdhMWE0Nzk=
_bW9kPWhwX2xlYWRfcG9zMQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB238b8b28" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> had its=
 best quarter ever</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Swiss bank lost more than $2 billion from =
its businesses in the first quarter, but posted a prodigious net profit bec=
ause of the paper gains realized from writing off $17 billion in bonds. =E2=
=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Credit Suisse posted a 12.43 billion Swiss fra=
nc net profit, equivalent to $13.9 billion, for the first three months of t=
he year because of the value of the written-off bonds. The bank lurched thr=
ough financial losses and scandals in the past several years, and failed in=
 a last attempt to restructure and regain trust after bank customers starte=
d pulling their deposits and investments last fall.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The massive quarterly profit, the largest in t=
he bank=E2=80=99s history and among the largest ever for a bank, is an unus=
ual coda given the bank=E2=80=99s unraveling.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It was possible because the write-down of the =
bonds feeds through as a revenue gain, which leads to a swelling of paper p=
rofits. But it isn=E2=80=99t money that Credit Suisse shareholders will imm=
ediately realize. UBS benefits, however, since it inherits Credit Suisse wi=
thout having to repay those bonds. Credit Suisse shareholders will receive =
UBS stock once the deal completes.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Credit Suisse is still an independent bank, an=
d as a technical accounting matter if it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/31280636.259437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9v=
cGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjAvdWJzLWdvdC1jcmVkaXQtc3Vpc3NlLWZvci1hbG1=
vc3Qtbm90aGluZz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNDI1MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJn=
V0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA0MjUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c=
3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf09d492a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  wrote down $17 billion=
 of additional tier 1 capital securities</a> to zero, that=E2=80=99s $17 bi=
llion of profit. Those are the rules. The fact that it wrote down those sec=
urities=C2=A0<em>because it collapsed </em>is of economic interest, but not=
 relevant to the accounting.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, because Credit Suisse was, as an account=
ing matter, well capitalized before, during and after its collapse, it is n=
ow=C2=A0<em>extremely=C2=A0</em>well capitalized, because all of those liab=
ilities went to zero. It reported a common equity tier 1 capital ratio of 1=
4.1% at the end of 2022, well above requirements; that number was 20.3% at =
the end of March because of the AT1 writedown.<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Credit Suisse is now an especially well-capitalized bank,=C2=A0<e=
m>because it failed</em>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And while Credit Suisse had one of the best qu=
arters in banking ever, because it failed, UBS is going to have=C2=A0<em>th=
e=C2=A0</em>best quarter in banking ever=C2=A0<em>next=C2=A0</em>quarter, <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31280636.259437/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMjUvdWJzLXNlZX=
MtY3JlZGl0LXN1aXNzZS1kZWFsLWNsb3NpbmctaW4tbWF5LWV4cGVjdHMtdG8tcG9zdC1nYWluP=
2NtcGlkPUJCRDA0MjUyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1u=
