<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Getty</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let=E2=80=99s say there=E2=80=99s a smallish p=
ublic company that you like. To make things more concrete, say it=E2=80=99s=
 Getty Images Holdings Inc., which went public last year by merging with a =
special purpose acquisition company; last Friday its stock closed at $5.06 =
per share, for an equity market capitalization of $2 billion. You buy some =
stock, expecting it to go up. It does not go up. You think the company coul=
d do a better job =E2=80=94=C2=A0you think it has a valuable business but m=
anagement is not maximizing its potential =E2=80=94=C2=A0so you send some l=
etters to the executives and board of directors with your ideas for improve=
ments. You get no answer, and things do not improve.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You decide that these people don=E2=80=99t kno=
w what they=E2=80=99re doing and that the only way to maximize the company=
=E2=80=99s potential is if someone buys the company, fires management, and =
runs it in the way that you think is better. And you think that someone=C2=
=A0<em>would=C2=A0</em>do that: The company is valuable but mismanaged, and=
 a smart buyer could pay a premium for it and still make a lot of money by =
running it right.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So you send some more letters to the board say=
ing =E2=80=9Chey you should hire bankers to run an auction and find someone=
 to buy the company.=E2=80=9D Still no response.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now what do you do? Well:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Send more letters? That=E2=80=99s not=
 going very well.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>You=C2=A0</em>could go out and find someone to buy the company. Call up=
 potential buyers, explain the value proposition, and get one of them to pa=
y, say, $4 billion to buy the whole company at a premium. This is hard, tho=
ugh, because you don=E2=80=99t work there and can=E2=80=99t really commit t=
o anything on behalf of the company. You could call up a big private equity=
 firm and say =E2=80=9Chey you should buy Getty Images,=E2=80=9D and they w=
ill say =E2=80=9Chmm maybe, when can we start due diligence,=E2=80=9D and y=
ou will say =E2=80=9Coh I don=E2=80=99t know I don=E2=80=99t work there, wh=
y don=E2=80=99t you call them?=E2=80=9D Not that helpful. (In the specific =
case of Getty, it=E2=80=99s even harder, because three big shareholders =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0the Getty family, Koch Industries Inc. and Neuberger Berman Gro=
up LLC =E2=80=94=C2=A0combine to own about 85% of the company and control t=
he board, so it=E2=80=99s not like a hostile deal is possible: Any potentia=
l buyer would have to work with the board.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">
<em>You=C2=A0</em>could buy the whole company yourself. But it=E2=80=99s no=
t like you have $4 billion lying around.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is =E2=80=94=C2=A0and this is not legal =
or investing or M&amp;A or any other sort of advice =E2=80=94=C2=A0another =
option, sort of a combination of Options 2 and 3. It goes like this. You=C2=
=A0<em>put out a press release offering to buy the company yourself</em>. =
=E2=80=9CI will buy this company at $10 per share, or $4 billion total,=E2=
=80=9D you say. Because you do not have $4 billion, you make it clear in th=
e press release that your offer is contingent on financing, and on the boar=
d engaging with you.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What will happen? Well, maybe the board will c=
all you up and say =E2=80=9Chey, you=E2=80=99re right, we=E2=80=99d love to=
 sell for $4 billion.=E2=80=9D Then you start due diligence, you learn abou=
t the company, you negotiate a deal, and you figure out if it=E2=80=99s rea=
lly worth $4 billion. If it is, you call up some private equity firms and s=
ay =E2=80=9Chey, I=E2=80=99ve got this great deal to buy Getty Images, all =
I need is $4 billion, are you in?=E2=80=9D And you bring them in and they d=
o due diligence and maybe they agree to put up the $4 billion to finance yo=
ur deal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or maybe all of the private equity firms pass,=
 and then you go back to the board and say =E2=80=9Chey thanks it=E2=80=99s=
 been great dealing with you but my financing fell through, and the deal wa=
s contingent on financing, so there=E2=80=99s no deal.=E2=80=9D And then yo=
u shake hands and walk away friends, and maybe the board is inspired by you=
r efforts and=C2=A0<em>they=C2=A0</em>will go find a buyer.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or maybe the board continues to ignore you, yo=
u can=E2=80=99t do due diligence, so you can=E2=80=99t get anyone else inte=
rested, so you can=E2=80=99t raise any financing. Then you=E2=80=99re not a=
ny=C2=A0<em>worse=C2=A0</em>off than you were before. You were on the outsi=
de, asking the board to sell the company, and now you=E2=80=99re still on t=
he outside, asking the board to sell the company. But you=E2=80=99re a litt=
le better off, because you are asking the board to sell the company in a hi=
gher-profile, higher-pressure way. =E2=80=9CI am offering to buy the compan=
y for $4 billion=E2=80=9D creates a little more pressure on the board to re=
spond than =E2=80=9CI would like you to sell the company to someone else fo=
r $4 billion.=E2=80=9D The board has some sort of fiduciary obligation to c=
onsider any real takeover offer. Is this a real takeover offer? Well! Well.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also let=E2=80=99s be clear here, you are bett=
er off in another way, which is that when you put out a press release offer=
ing to buy the company at a huge premium, the stock will go up. And you own=
 some stock. Something to think about!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is this =E2=80=A6=C2=A0is this what you would =
call a=C2=A0<em>fake=C2=A0</em>takeover offer? I don=E2=80=99t know! On the=
 one hand, you are offering to buy the company for $4 billion, and you don=
=E2=80=99t have $4 billion, so there is something a bit off about that. On =
the other hand, you did=C2=A0<em>say=C2=A0</em>that your offer was continge=
nt on financing and due diligence. =E2=80=9CI will buy this company for $4 =
billion if someone will give me $4 billion,=E2=80=9D is the essential conte=
nt of your announcement. Could be true! Anyone could buy a company for $4 b=
illion, if someone gave them $4 billion, and if the company agreed to sell.=
 Those are big ifs, but they are right in the announcement.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here is an <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31280636.259437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucHJuZXdzd2lyZS=
5jb20vbmV3cy1yZWxlYXNlcy90cmlsbGl1bS1jYXBpdGFsLWlzc3N1ZXMtcHJvcG9zYWwtdG8tY=
