=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> Treasury bills</a> or money market funds. Me=
anwhile the market interest rates on mortgages and Treasury bonds have also=
 gone up; the 10-year Treasury yields about 3.4% and <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31280636.259437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMTkvdXMtMzAteWVhci1tb3J0Z2FnZS1yYXR=
lLWNsaW1icy1ieS1tb3N0LWluLXR3by1tb250aHMtdG8tNi00Mz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNDI1MjNfTU=
9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVyb=
T0yMzA0MjUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1ff6289=
4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  mortgage rates</a> are at like 6.4%.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is potentially bad news for banks. There =
are two ways for that to go. It can be=C2=A0<em>acutely=C2=A0</em>bad news.=
 Acute bad news looks like this:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A bank=E2=80=99s=C2=A0assets =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0its bonds and loans =E2=80=94=C2=A0have=C2=A0<em>lost value:=C2=A0</e=
m>If you have $100 million=C2=A0of 3% mortgages, and mortgage rates are now=
 6%, your old 3% mortgages might be worth $85 million.<a class=3D"footnote-=
index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; di=
splay: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0You have a large mark-to-market loss on your assets because inter=
est rates have moved against you.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
Meanwhile the bank=E2=80=99s depositors will=C2=A0<em>take their money out<=
/em>, because (1) they can get more interest elsewhere and/or (2) they are =
worried about the bank=E2=80=99s=C2=A0solvency because of all the mark-to-m=
arket losses on its assets.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The ba=
nk needs to get cash to pay those depositors, which it does by selling bond=
s and loans, but since those are less valuable than they used to be it can=
=E2=80=99t raise enough money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The=
 bank goes bust, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. seizes it, it pays out=
 depositors and it auctions off the assets at a loss.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This acute bad news is more or less what happe=
ned to Silicon Valley Bank last month. Standard bank-run stuff.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it could also be=C2=A0<em>chronically=C2=
=A0</em>bad news, which is probably less bad. Chronic bad news looks like t=
his:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Never mind the stuff about the assets =
losing value. That is a matter of accounting, and you can ignore it. If you=
 have $100 million of 3% mortgages, and mortgage rates are now 6%, you stil=
l have $100 million of 3% mortgages. They will still pay you back $100 mill=
ion=C2=A0plus interest. It=E2=80=99s just that the interest is less than yo=
u=E2=80=99d like, less than the current market rate. You still have the sam=
e assets, but they pay you 3%;=C2=A0<em>new=C2=A0</em>assets would pay 6%.<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Meanwhile the bank=E2=80=99s depos=
itors don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>take their money out:=C2=A0</em>They just=C2=
=A0<em>charge=C2=A0</em>more. The bank keeps its deposits by=C2=A0<em>payin=
g interest=C2=A0</em>to compete with Treasury bills and money market funds.=
=C2=A0It doesn=E2=80=99t have any more depositors in zero-interest checking=
 accounts, but it has depositors who get 5% on their savings accounts.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The bank doesn=E2=80=99t need to raise=
 cash, it doesn=E2=80=99t sell assets, it doesn=E2=80=99t go bust, the FDIC=
 doesn=E2=80=99t seize it, everything is fine.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">It=E2=80=99s just that, you know, it is earning 3% on its mone=
y and paying 5%, so it=E2=80=99s losing 2% each year. It is not=C2=A0<em>pr=
ofitable</em>.=C2=A0<em>Eventually=C2=A0</em>it will run out of money.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Meh! That can change. For one thing, t=
hose 3% mortgages will mature, and the bank will make more mortgages at 6%;=
 eventually its assets will turn over and it will earn market interest rate=
s on them. And as things stabilize a bit, it will probably get back more of=
 its zero-interest deposit accounts and pay a bit less for its money. Event=
ually things will get back to normal and the bank will be paying 3% on depo=
sits, earning 6% on loans, and making the same spread as it was before.<a c=
lass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpare=
nt !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0It just has to weather some unpleasantness to get there.</li>
</ul>
